1. + in Rust is the Add trait

When you write:
    let c = a + b;

Rust literally translates it to:
    let c = a.add(b);

where Add is defined like this:
    pub trait Add<Rhs = Self> {
        type Output;

        fn add(self, rhs: Rhs) -> Self::Output;
    }

2. The important part: ownership is in the signature

For String, the implementation is:

    impl Add<&str> for String {
        type Output = String;

        fn add(mut self, rhs: &str) -> String {
            self.push_str(rhs);
            self
        }
    }


3. What this really means

When you write:
    let a = String::from("Hello");
    let b = " world";

    let c = a + b;

Rust rewrites it as:

    let mut a = String::from("Hello");

    a.push_str(b);

    let c = a;

So:

Key behavior:
- a is moved into the function
- b is borrowed (&str)
- a is mutated in place
result is returned as String


4. Why self matters (this is the core idea)

Notice:
    fn add(mut self, rhs: &str)

self is not a reference — it is:
    ownership of the left operand is transferred into the function

So Rust is saying:
- “I will take your string”
- “I will modify it”
- “I will give it back”

This avoids copying entirely.


5. Why only &str, not String?

This is the key design decision:

If Rust allowed:
    impl Add<String> for String

then this would exist:
    fn add(self, rhs: String)

But now both sides are owned.

That forces a decision:
    Option A: copy RHS

clone rhs → append → return
    Option B: move RHS

But then:

- you destroy rhs
- behavior becomes asymmetric and confusing


6. Rust chooses: only one side is consumed

So Rust standardizes:
    String + &str

Meaning:
- left side is consumed (moved)
- right side is borrowed (no ownership transfer)

This gives:
- no unnecessary cloning
- predictable cost
- consistent memory behavior


7. Why this is efficient (important insight)

Because String is:
    (pointer, length, capacity)

So add can:

Step 1: reuse existing buffer
No new allocation required (if capacity is enough)

Step 2: append bytes directly
    [H e l l o] + [   w o r l d]

Step 3: return same buffer
So the operation is basically:
    “extend existing allocation”

8. Why Rust does NOT use implicit cloning

If Rust allowed implicit String + String, it would often do:
    clone lhs + clone rhs → new allocation

That:
- hides performance cost
- hides memory allocations
- makes code behavior unpredictable

Rust avoids “surprise work”.


9. Why format! exists

Because Rust separates concerns:

Task	                    Tool
efficient append	        push_str
consume + append	        + &str
create new string safely	format!

format! is basically:
    fn format(...) -> String {
        allocate new String
        write everything into it
    }


10. Mental model that usually helps

Think of + as:
- take ownership of left
- borrow right
- append right into left
- return left

NOT:
- create new string from both



If you want one takeaway

Rust’s string design is not about making things shorter.

It is about making this explicit:
    “Did this allocate? Did this move? Did this copy?”

Once that mental model locks in, string handling actually becomes very predictable, even if it feels verbose at first.